recordings.rmk:
Modification: filtering to account for strong wind, removal of microphone bumps
Habitat: area is filled with burned stands and new growth of Ponderosa Pine, Subalpine Larch, and Fir lining a subalpine lake surrounded by thick shrubs. Bird was about 15 feet away 10 feet up on a pine snag that swayed in the wind
Behavior: bird was flying the area, circling territory, and singing from individual perches for 5-10 minutes before moving to the next
sex: Male

It was a fairly windy day at Roger Lake, as can be heard later in the recording especially. The wind grabbing my parabolic microphone, necessitating the removal of microphone bumps. Fortunately the bird didn't seem to care and kept singing clearly through the whole affair. Only his occasional head turns and the windy swaying of the tree he was in caused tonal and dynamic variation in his song.

recordings.loc: Blairsville, Union County, Georgia
recordings.rmk: This species has nested in a small scrubby patch of willow for many years.  It is - to the best of my knowledge - the only regular breeding location of the species in the state of Georgia.  There were actually two birds singing.  The location is very near a main artery of traffic through the town of Blairsville, and my vantage point is the only approach. Consequently there was a lot of morning noise and the recording is highly modified to accentuate the flycatcher, including noise reduction and high-pass filtering as well as discarding some sounds within the recording which would alter any perceived cadence of intervals between songs.

recordings.loc: 4 (near  Mansfield), Red River Parish, Louisiana
recordings.rmk: Fol xc277371.  Vocalizations begin with agonistic trill at end of 0:8 then bout of excited and somewhat rapid song bursts can be heard shortly thereafter. Aside from occasional mimicked "fitzbew and "wit" calls given by me, playback had been discontinued quite some time before this recording was made-

recordings.loc: 4 (near  Mansfield), Red River Parish, Louisiana
recordings.rmk: Fol xc277301. "whip" call at 0:1 is possibly Y-b Chat but sounds nearly identical to some variable "wit"-type calls of willow Fly males. Again, brief playback had been discontinued some time earlier- but bird may still have been responding to that from earlier- along with scattered imitated calls by me used thereafter. Although single "fitz-bew" songs are often given, I've suspected for years whether a "complete" song, usually heard given by rare local breeders here in nw La (and elsewhere?), is not actually three-parted- consisting of an initial "fitzbew.......creet....reet-beeyr" or mixed variations thereof of these three distinct calls.

Island in Rio Napo, Orellana
recordings.rmk: Calls in response to playback from two individuals (on opposite sides of a channel) on young river island with grass, Gynerium, Cecropias, and small Tessaria. The first on-mic bird (which sounded odd, almost like E. alnorum, but reverted to a typical 'whit' note after I ended the recording) was perched about 1-2m up. The second on-mic bird was farther away (in-line with the river, hence the louder motor noise) and sounded more typical of E. traillii. recordings.loc: "The Annex" Homestead, Miami-Dade, Florida
recordings.rmk: This is a recording of multiple "whit" calls of a Willow Flycatcher. The recording was made using the "voice memo" app on an iPhone 4S. The recording was slightly amplified using Audacity but is otherwise unedited. This bird has been present for nearly two months at this location, which is quite unusual, especially since this species is rarely recorded in Florida. The habitat is dense tropical shrubby hammock along a canal and road edge adjacent to a large open field. The area is just outside of the main entrance to Everglades National Park. The bird spent most of its time calling from deep within cover 5-10 feet off the ground. It briefly flew across the road and perched in the open and called a few more times. Poor photos were obtained in the early morning light.

Matches the '2H' sonogram illustrated in the [BNA account for Willow Flycatcher](http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/533/articles/sounds) (retrieved June 5, 2013), which is described as follows:

> Sound similar to writ-tus and vaguely like fitz-bews but somewhat buzzier (Fig. 2H); structurally resemble a creet followed by a descending writ-tu (compare Figs. 2D, 2E, and 2H); given infrequently in aggressive contexts.

Bird seen, but species ID based solely on voice.

recordings.loc: Tongass National Forest (near  Yakutat), Yakutat, Alaska
recordings.rmk:
Rare bird for this area. Sound recorded to document this species. Mp4 video taken with Panasonic Lumix camera and file then converted to .mp3 sound with Zamar free online conversion. 

Observations.  Immediately recognized song (have heard it in Montana and California). Distinct from the more common Alder flycatchers in area as it is longer and generally two parted. The mnemonic sounds to me like “zip….. zipadedooo”.  Field marks: generally, a swarthy Empidonax type, with only a wash of yellow on light lower parts, fairly dark brownish gray upper parts, bill wide, eye ring minimal, throat silvery gray, double wing bars dull white. Drooped wings, and threw back head with a lot of energy when sings. Mostly perched concealed in willow but occasionally rested atop spruce cones. While out of normal range, habitat should be good for the species: extensive clumps of thick Salix sp. willows, creek edge nearby, many insects.
